Chapter 1
Cohren
4:30 a.m., time in Itania. Cohren hated waking up so early. Especially since it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his squad. Silently getting out of bed, he put on his combat uniform, fastened his tactical vest, and gathered the items from his locker, paying particular attention to a small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and attached his helmet to a small hook on his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: respirator, goggles, everything necessary. After checking his ammunition pockets, he calmly walked out of the barracks, the sound of crushed mud and ice echoing under his boots.
He took out a lighter from the pocket of his vest and a cigarette from the other. As he lit it, he took a small puff before gently opening the door. Last week, he had had to be creative to wake up the men and women under his command. He had stopped using the pre-set alarm; half the time, it didn't work, since all that came out of the speakers was a faint hiss.
"Are you waking them up?" Cohren turned around to see Second Lieutenant Nemic approaching on foot.
"Certainement," replied Cohren.
"What are you planning to use this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and other soldiers hurried out, already dressed and equipped.
"Hello," said Craith.
"What woke you up?" asked Cohren.
"Well then, first of all, we didn't want to see what you had planned to wake us up today. Second, the first shock troops on their feet are the first to have breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be."
"You're right, Specialist," said Cohren. He reached out and activated a switch. An alarm rang out inside the hut, loud and piercing. He heard commotion and confusion inside.
"Good grief, Valturi," said Nemic. "One would think that by now they'd have learned to rise at the same time as you."
"Well, my buddies from the training camp here have done it," Cohren turned to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "But, again, their group and section leaders know how to get up before their units."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company emerged en masse. They all had what they needed, from personal belongings to essential equipment. Some of the new recruits seemed disoriented, while others appeared more annoyed.
"Hello everyone," said Cohren in a cheerful voice.
"Except your respect, chef, why are you so stubborn about waking us up this way?" asked one of the shock troop members, a corporal.
"Because standard wake-ups are terrible. And because Daybreak doesn't do lazy mornings," replied Cohren.
"He made sure to have all his personal belongings," he continued. As the first lieutenant and assistant to the commander, it was his responsibility to supervise and assist the company under the command of the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We are not coming back. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I give you fifty minutes to complete your final checks and retrieve rations for the day."
The members of Exodus Company scattered. They were part of the second division of the shock troops, the second army. Initially, they were split into two distinct companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being reunited. It was a scattered company, and Cohren didn't know what to think about his promotion to first lieutenant, mainly for reasons that had motivated him.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first squad, walked together under the light of the numerous lights from the forward operating base, powered by generators. Most were tinted red to hide them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had used both air and ground Wild Weasel assaults to combat them.
"Nouveau jour, nouvelle mission for the pioneers of hell," Nemic began with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"An advanced operational base outside Ianlos. We were sent to support the ground assault," Cohren replied, taking a drag on his cigarette. Part of him blamed Craith for introducing him to smoking, but a year of combat changes a man, and he said nothing.
"Damn it. The situation is deteriorating on the front," muttered Nemic. "All the news coming from this place is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send aid to the Kurgan front.' Why not send aid to the Howland front?"
"Amen, my brother," said Cohren, flicking his cigarette butt into the mud. "Anyway, we're leaving with the first armored unit, so we won't have to march. Captain Shaw should be there."
"Did Shaw get a ride for us?" asked Nemic, a bit surprised.
"Ugh. Honestly, it's not as bad as I thought. I mean, it's not exceptional, but it's not unbearable."
Cohren placed his thumb and index finger on his throat mic while adjusting his backpack. "All units of the Exodus company, report to the west vehicle park when you're done. We're departing with the first armored squad at 5:00 a.m."
Every few seconds, he received replies from the squad leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik had all been low-ranking junior officers when they arrived here. All four had been very close friends since their initial training on Earth. It seemed like such a long time ago, even though it couldn't have been more than two years. They had then been squad leaders. But Craith had been commanding the second squad for a week now, following the demobilization of the previous commander, who had been wounded by an elite marksman from Daybreak.
As they walked toward the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic saw a group of about eight main Kronos combat tanks and four Strykers. Their crews were busy, ensuring their war machines were ready for departure. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was speaking with the commander of the armored squad. As they approached, Shaw turned and walked toward them, his usually cold face showing no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said that Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's gun holster before looking at them again. "I suppose the company is ready."
